<DOC><DOCNO> AP890310-0097 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-10-89 1038EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-US-Syria     03-10 0245</FIRST><SECOND>PM-US-Syria,230</SECOND><HEAD>U.S. Says Palestinian Group Held Two American Diplomats In Syria</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Palestinian group based in Syria detained twoAmerican diplomats for more than eight hours before handing themover to Syrian authorities, the State Department says.   ``The two embassy officials were not harmed,'' press officerNancy Beck said Thursday, adding that the U.S. government filed aprotest with the Syrian government on Thursday over the March 3incident.   Ms. Beck said she didn't have the names of the U.S. officials.   She said armed members of the Popular Front for the Liberation ofPalestine-General Command stopped and detained the officials outsidethe Damascus area, holding them ``for over eight hours'' until theywere turned over to Syrian authorities.   ``The Syrian government immediately contacted the U.S. Embassyand turned over our personnel to the embassy,'' Ms. Beck said.   ``Today we are registering our strong protest of this incident tothe Syrian government, stressing that we hold it responsible for thesafety of our diplomatic personnel,'' she said.   ``We once again urge Syria to take action against the PFLP-GCterrorist group to insure that there is no repetition of suchincidents and that it end its activities,'' Ms. Beck said.   ``Because the PFLP-GC is headquartered in Damascus, Syria mustbear responsibility for its actions,'' she said.   The PFLP-GC is a faction formed by Ahmed Jibril, an officer inthe Syrian army, in 1968. Most of its attacks have been againstIsraeli targets.</TEXT></DOC>